#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:5
msgid "Wasm Workers API"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:7
msgid ""
"The Wasm Workers API enables C/C++ code to leverage Web Workers and shared "
"WebAssembly.Memory (SharedArrayBuffer) to build multithreaded programs via a "
"direct web-like programming API."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:12
msgid "Quick Example"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:30
msgid ""
"Build the code by passing the Emscripten flag ``-sWASM_WORKERS`` at both "
"compile and link steps. The example code creates a new Worker on the main "
"browser thread, which shares the same WebAssembly.Module and WebAssembly."
"Memory object. Then a ``postMessage()`` is passed to the Worker to ask it to "
"execute the function ``run_in_worker()`` to print a string."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:36
msgid ""
"To explicitly control the memory allocation placement when creating a "
"worker, use the ``emscripten_create_wasm_worker()`` function. This function "
"takes a region of memory that must be large enough to hold both the stack "
"and the TLS data for the worker.  You can use ``__builtin_wasm_tls_size()`` "
"to find out at runtime how much space is required for the program's TLS data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:43
msgid "Introduction"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:45
msgid ""
"In WebAssembly programs, the Memory object that contains the application "
"state can be shared across multiple Workers. This enables direct, high "
"performance (and if explicit care is not taken, racy!) access to "
"synchronously share data state between multiple Workers (shared state "
"multithreading)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:50
msgid ""
"Emscripten supports two multithreading APIs to leverage this web feature:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:51
msgid "POSIX Threads (Pthreads) API, and"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:52
msgid "Wasm Workers API."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:54
msgid ""
"The Pthreads API has a long history with native C programming and the POSIX "
"standard, while Wasm Workers API is unique to Emscripten compiler only."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:57
msgid ""
"These two APIs provide largely the same feature set, but have important "
"differences, which this documentation seeks to explain to help decide which "
"API one should target."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:61
msgid "Pthreads vs Wasm Workers: Which One to Use?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:63
msgid ""
"The intended audience and use cases of these two multithreading APIs are "
"slightly different."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:66
msgid ""
"The focus on Pthreads API is on portability and cross-platform "
"compatibility. This API is best used in scenarios where portability is most "
"important, e.g. when a codebase is cross-compiled to multiple platforms, "
"like building both a native Linux x64 executable and an Emscripten "
"WebAssembly based web site."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:71
msgid ""
"Pthreads API in Emscripten seeks to carefully emulate compatibility and the "
"features that the native Pthreads platforms already provide. This helps "
"porting large C/C++ codebases over to WebAssembly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:75
msgid ""
"Wasm Workers API on the other hand seeks to provide a \"direct mapping\" to "
"the web multithreading primitives as they exist on the web, and call it a "
"day. If an application is only developed to target WebAssembly, and "
"portability is not a concern, then using Wasm Workers can provide great "
"benefits in the form of simpler compiled output, less complexity, smaller "
"code size and possibly better performance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:81
msgid ""
"However this benefit might not be an obvious win. The Pthreads API was "
"designed to be useful from the synchronous C/C++ language, whereas Web "
"Workers are designed to be useful from asynchronous JavaScript. WebAssembly "
"C/C++ programs can find themselves somewhere in the middle."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:86
msgid "Pthreads and Wasm Workers share several similarities:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:88
msgid "Both can use emscripten_atomic_* Atomics API,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:89
msgid "Both can use emscripten_futex_wait/wake API,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:90
msgid "Both can use GCC __sync_* Atomics API,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:91
msgid "Both can use C11 and C++11 Atomics APIs,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:92
msgid "Both types of threads have a local stack."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:93
msgid ""
"Both types of threads have thread-local storage (TLS) support via "
"``thread_local`` (C++11), ``_Thread_local`` (C11) and ``__thread`` (GNU11) "
"keywords."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:95
msgid ""
"Both types of threads support TLS via explicitly linked in Wasm globals (see "
"``test/wasm_worker/wasm_worker_tls_wasm_assembly.c/.S`` for example code)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:97
msgid ""
"Both types of threads have a concept of a thread ID (``pthread_self()`` for "
"pthreads, ``emscripten_wasm_worker_self_id()`` for Wasm Workers).  "
"`gettid()` works in both contexts so is more portable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:100
msgid ""
"Both types of threads can perform an event-based and an infinite loop "
"programming model."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:101
msgid ""
"Both can use ``EM_ASM`` and ``EM_JS`` API to execute JS code on the calling "
"thread."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:102
msgid ""
"Both can call out to JS library functions (linked in with ``--js-library`` "
"directive) to execute JS code on the calling thread."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:104
msgid ""
"Neither pthreads nor Wasm Workers can be used in conjunction with ``-"
"sSINGLE_FILE`` linker flag."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:106
msgid "However, the differences are more notable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:109
msgid "C11 thread APIs are not available under Wasm Workers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:111
msgid ""
"Becuase our C11 threading API is based on pthreads internally these APIs are "
"not available under Wasm Worker."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:115
msgid "Some standard C++ APIs are not available under Wasm Workers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:117
msgid ""
"Some parts of the libc++ stndard library are not available under Wasm "
"Workers becuase they depend on pthreads internally.  For example `std::"
"call_once``: https://github.com/emscripten-core/emscripten/issues/26375."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:122
msgid "Pthreads can proxy JS functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:124
msgid ""
"Only pthreads can use the ``MAIN_THREAD_EM_ASM*()`` and "
"``MAIN_THREAD_ASYNC_EM_ASM()`` functions and the ``foo__proxy: "
"'sync'/'async'`` proxying directive in JS libraries."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:127
msgid ""
"Wasm Workers on the other hand do not provide a built-in JS function "
"proxying facility. Proxying a JS function with Wasm Workers can be done by "
"explicitly passing the address of that function to the "
"``emscripten_wasm_worker_post_function_*`` API."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:131
msgid ""
"If you need to synchronously wait for the posted function to finish from "
"within a Worker, use one of the ``emscripten_wasm_worker_*()`` thread "
"synchronization functions to sleep the calling thread until the callee has "
"finished the operation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:136
msgid "Pthreads have cancellation points"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:138
msgid ""
"At the expense of performance and code size, pthreads implement a notion of "
"**POSIX cancellation points** (``pthread_cancel()``, "
"``pthread_testcancel()``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:141
msgid ""
"Wasm Workers are more lightweight and performant by not enabling that "
"concept."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:144
msgid ""
"Pthreads may start up synchronously - Wasm Workers always start "
"asynchronously"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:146
msgid ""
"Creating new Workers can be slow. Spawning a Worker in JavaScript is an "
"asynchronous operation. In order to support synchronous pthread startup (for "
"applications that need it) and to improve thread startup performance, "
"pthreads are hosted in a cached Emscripten runtime managed Worker pool."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:150
msgid ""
"Wasm Workers omit this concept, and as result Wasm Workers will always start "
"up asynchronously. If you need to detect when a Wasm Worker has started up, "
"post a ping-pong function and reply pair manually between the Worker and its "
"creator. If you need to spin up new threads quickly, consider managing a "
"pool of Wasm Workers yourself."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:156
msgid "Pthread topology is flat - Wasm Workers are hierarchical"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:158
msgid ""
"On the web, if a Worker spawns a child Worker of its own, it will create a "
"nested Worker hierarchy that the main thread cannot directly access. To "
"sidestep portability issues stemming from this kind of topology, pthreads "
"flatten the Worker creation chain under the hood so that only the main "
"browser thread ever spawns threads."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:163
msgid ""
"Wasm Workers do not implement this kind of topology flattening, and creating "
"a Wasm Worker in a Wasm Worker will produce a nested Worker hierarchy. If "
"you need to create Wasm Workers from within a Wasm Worker, consider which "
"type of hierarchy you would like, and if necessary, flatten the hierarchy "
"manually by posting the Worker creation over to the main thread yourself."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:168
msgid ""
"Note that support for nested Workers varies across browsers. As of 02/2022, "
"nested Workers are `not supported in Safari <https://webkit.org/b/22723>`_. "
"See `here <https://github.com/johanholmerin/nested-worker>`_ for a polyfill."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:173
msgid "Pthreads can use the Wasm Worker synchronization API"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:175
msgid ""
"The multithreading synchronization primitives offered in ``emscripten/"
"wasm_worker.h`` (``emscripten_lock_*``, ``emscripten_semaphore_*``, "
"``emscripten_condvar_*``) can be freely invoked from within pthreads if one "
"so wishes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:180
msgid "Wasm Workers cannot use the pthread API, unless building in hybrid mode"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:182
msgid ""
"By default, Wasm Workers cannot call any pthread APIs (``pthread_mutex_*``, "
"``pthread_cond_*``, ``pthread_self()``, etc.), since they lack the needed "
"thread metadata."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:186
msgid ""
"However, when building in **hybrid mode** (linking with both ``-"
"sWASM_WORKERS`` and ``-pthread``), Wasm Workers are created with the "
"additional metadata needed. In this mode, Wasm Workers support a subset of "
"the pthread API:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:190
msgid "``pthread_self()`` and ``pthread_equal()``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:191
msgid ""
"Thread Specific Data (TSD) via ``pthread_getspecific()`` and "
"``pthread_setspecific()``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:192
msgid ""
"Thread synchronization API such was `pthread_mutex_*` and `pthread_cond_*`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:194
msgid ""
"APIs that manage the thread lifecycle (like ``pthread_create``, "
"``pthread_join``, ``pthread_detach``, ``pthread_cancel``) are still not "
"supported for Wasm Workers, even in hybrid mode."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:199
msgid "Pthreads have a \"thread main\" function and atexit handlers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:201
msgid ""
"The startup/execution model of pthreads is to start up executing a given "
"thread entry point function. When that function exits, the pthread will also "
"(by default) quit, and the Worker hosting that pthread will return to the "
"Worker pool to wait for another thread to be created on it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:205
msgid ""
"Wasm Workers instead implement the direct web-like model, where a newly "
"created Worker sits idle in its event loop, waiting for functions to be "
"posted to it. When those functions finish, the Worker will return to its "
"event loop, waiting to receive more functions (or worker scope web events) "
"to execute. A Wasm Worker will only quit with a call to "
"``emscripten_terminate_wasm_worker(worker_id)`` or "
"``emscripten_terminate_all_wasm_workers()``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:211
msgid ""
"Pthreads allow one to register thread exit handlers via ``pthread_atexit``, "
"which will be called when the thread quits. Wasm Workers do not have this "
"concept."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:215
msgid ""
"Pthreads have a per-thread incoming proxy message queue, Wasm Workers do not"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:217
msgid ""
"In order to enable flexible synchronous execution of code on other threads, "
"and to implement support APIs for example for MEMFS filesystem and Offscreen "
"Framebuffer (WebGL emulated from a Worker) features, main browser thread and "
"each pthread have a system-backed \"proxy message queue\" to receive "
"messages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:221
msgid ""
"This enables user code to call API functions, "
"``emscripten_sync_run_in_main_runtime_thread()``, "
"``emscripten_async_run_in_main_runtime_thread()``, "
"``emscripten_dispatch_to_thread()``, etc. from ``emscripten/threading.h`` to "
"perform proxied calls."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:225
msgid ""
"Wasm Workers do not provide this functionality. If needed, such messaging "
"should be implemented manually by users via regular multithreaded "
"synchronized programming techniques (mutexes, futexes, semaphores, etc.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:229
msgid "Pthreads synchronize wallclock times"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:231
msgid ""
"Another portability aiding emulation feature that Pthreads provide is that "
"the time values returned by ``emscripten_get_now()`` are synchronized to a "
"common time base across all threads."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:234
msgid ""
"Wasm Workers omit this concept, and it is recommended to use the function "
"``emscripten_performance_now()`` for high performance timing in a Wasm "
"Worker, and avoid comparing resulting values across Workers, or manually "
"synchronize them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:239
msgid "Input events API backproxies only to pthreads"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:241
msgid ""
"The multithreaded input API provided in ``emscripten/html5.h`` only works "
"with the pthread API. When calling any of the functions "
"``emscripten_set_*_callback_on_thread()``, one can choose the target pthread "
"to be the recipient of the received events."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:245
msgid ""
"With Wasm Workers, if desired, \"backproxying\" events from the main browser "
"thread to a Wasm Worker should be implemented manually e.g. by using the "
"``emscripten_wasm_worker_post_function_*()`` API family."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:248
msgid ""
"However note that backproxying input events has a drawback that it prevents "
"security sensitive operations, like fullscreen requests, pointer locking and "
"audio playback resuming, since handling the input event is detached from the "
"event callback context executing the initial operation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:253
msgid "Pthread vs emscripten_lock implementation differences"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:255
msgid ""
"The mutex implementation from ``pthread_mutex_*`` has a few different "
"creation options, one being a \"recursive\" mutex."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:258
msgid ""
"The lock implemented by ``emscripten_lock_*`` API is not recursive (and does "
"not provide an option)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:260
msgid ""
"Pthreads also offer a programming guard against a programming error that one "
"thread would not release a lock that is owned by another thread. "
"``emscripten_lock_*`` API does not track lock ownership."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:264
msgid "Memory requirements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:266
msgid ""
"Pthreads have a fixed dependency to dynamic memory allocation, and perform "
"calls to ``malloc`` and ``free`` to allocate thread specific data, stacks "
"and TLS slots."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:269
msgid ""
"With the exception of the helper function "
"``emscripten_malloc_wasm_worker()``, Wasm Workers are not dependent on a "
"dynamic memory allocator. Memory allocation needs are met by the caller at "
"Worker creation time, and can be statically placed if desired."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:274
msgid "Generated code size"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:276
msgid ""
"The disk size overhead from pthreads is on the order of a few hundred KBs. "
"Wasm Workers runtime on the other hand is optimized for tiny deployments, "
"just a few hundred bytes on disk."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:280
msgid "API Differences"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:282
msgid ""
"To further understand the different APIs available between Pthreads and Wasm "
"Workers, refer to the following table."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:285
msgid ""
"<table style='border:solid 2px;' cellpadding=10>\n"
"  <tr><td class='cellborder'>Feature</td>\n"
"  <td class='cellborder'>Pthreads</td>\n"
"  <td class='cellborder'>Wasm Workers</td> </tr>\n"
"\n"
"  <tr><td class='cellborder'>Thread termination</td>\n"
"  <td class='cellborder'>Thread calls <pre>pthread_exit(status)</pre>or main "
"thread calls <pre>pthread_kill(code)</pre></td>\n"
"  <td class='cellborder'>Worker cannot terminate itself, parent thread "
"terminates by calling <pre>emscripten_terminate_wasm_worker(worker)</pre></"
"td></tr>\n"
"\n"
"  <tr><td class='cellborder'>Thread stack</td>\n"
"  <td class='cellborder'>Specify in pthread_attr_t structure.</td>\n"
"  <td class='cellborder'>Manage thread stack area explicitly with "
"<pre>emscripten_create_wasm_worker_*_tls()</pre> functions, or\n"
"    <br>automatically allocate stack+TLS area with "
"<pre>emscripten_malloc_wasm_worker()</pre> API.</td></tr>\n"
"\n"
"  <tr><td class='cellborder'>Thread Local Storage (TLS)</td>\n"
"  <td class='cellborder'>Supported transparently.</td>\n"
"  <td class='cellborder'>Supported either explicitly with "
"<pre>emscripten_create_wasm_worker_*_tls()</pre> functions, or\n"
"    <br>automatically via <pre>emscripten_malloc_wasm_worker()</pre> API.</"
"td></tr>\n"
"\n"
"  <tr><td class='cellborder'>Thread ID</td>\n"
"  <td class='cellborder'>Creating a pthread obtains its ID. Call "
"<pre>pthread_self()</pre> to acquire ID of calling thread.</td>\n"
"  <td class='cellborder'>Creating a Worker obtains its ID. Call "
"<pre>emscripten_wasm_worker_self_id()</pre> acquire ID of calling thread."
"<br>In hybrid mode, <pre>pthread_self()</pre> also works.</td></tr>\n"
"\n"
"  <tr><td class='cellborder'>High resolution timer</td>\n"
"  <td class='cellborder'>``emscripten_get_now()``</td>\n"
"  <td class='cellborder'>``emscripten_performance_now()``</td></tr>\n"
"\n"
"  <tr><td class='cellborder'>Synchronous blocking on main thread</td>\n"
"  <td class='cellborder'>Synchronization primitives internally fall back to "
"busy spin loops.</td>\n"
"  <td class='cellborder'>Explicit spin vs sleep synchronization primitives.</"
"td></tr>\n"
"\n"
"  <tr><td class='cellborder'>Futex API</td>\n"
"  <td class='cellborder'><pre>emscripten_futex_wait</"
"pre><pre>emscripten_futex_wake</pre> in emscripten/threading.h</td>\n"
"  <td class='cellborder'><pre>emscripten_atomic_wait_u32</"
"pre><pre>emscripten_atomic_wait_u64</pre><pre>emscripten_atomic_notify</pre> "
"in emscripten/atomic.h</td></tr>\n"
"\n"
"  <tr><td class='cellborder'>Asynchronous futex wait</td>\n"
"  <td class='cellborder'>N/A</td>\n"
"  <td class='cellborder'><pre>emscripten_atomic_wait_async()</"
"pre><pre>emscripten_*_async_acquire()</pre>However these are a difficult "
"footgun, read <a href='https://github.com/WebAssembly/threads/"
"issues/176'>WebAssembly/threads issue #176</a></td></tr>\n"
"\n"
"  <tr><td class='cellborder'>C/C++ Function Proxying</td>\n"
"  <td class='cellborder'>emscripten/threading.h API for proxying function "
"calls to other threads.</td>\n"
"  <td class='cellborder'>Use emscripten_wasm_worker_post_function_*() API to "
"message functions to other threads. These messages follow event queue "
"semantics rather than proxy queue semantics.</td></tr>\n"
"\n"
"  <tr><td class='cellborder'>Build flags</td>\n"
"  <td class='cellborder'>Compile and link with -pthread</td>\n"
"  <td class='cellborder'>Compile and link with -sWASM_WORKERS</td></tr>\n"
"\n"
"  <tr><td class='cellborder'>Preprocessor directives</td>\n"
"  <td class='cellborder'>__EMSCRIPTEN_SHARED_MEMORY__=1 and "
"__EMSCRIPTEN_PTHREADS__=1 are active</td>\n"
"  <td class='cellborder'>__EMSCRIPTEN_SHARED_MEMORY__=1 and "
"__EMSCRIPTEN_WASM_WORKERS__=1 are active</td></tr>\n"
"\n"
"  <tr><td class='cellborder'>JS library directives</td>\n"
"  <td class='cellborder'>USE_PTHREADS and SHARED_MEMORY are active</td>\n"
"  <td class='cellborder'>USE_PTHREADS, SHARED_MEMORY and WASM_WORKER are "
"active</td></tr>\n"
"\n"
"  <tr><td class='cellborder'>Atomics API</td>\n"
"  <td colspan=2>Supported, use any of <a href=\"https://gcc.gnu.org/"
"onlinedocs/gcc/_005f_005fatomic-Builtins.html\">__atomic_* API</a>, <a "
"href=\"https://llvm.org/docs/Atomics.html#libcalls-sync\">__sync_* API</a> "
"or <a href=\"https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/atomic/atomic\">C++11 std::"
"atomic API</a>.</td></tr>\n"
"\n"
"  <tr><td class='cellborder'>Nonrecursive mutex</td>\n"
"  <td class='cellborder'><pre>pthread_mutex_*</pre></td>\n"
