#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:376
msgid "Wasm Workers stack size considerations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:378
msgid ""
"When instantiating a Wasm Worker, one has to create a memory array for the "
"LLVM data stack for the created Worker. This data stack will generally "
"consist only of local variables that have been \"spilled\" by LLVM into "
"memory, e.g. to contain large arrays, structs, or other variables that are "
"referenced by a memory address. This stack will not contain control flow "
"information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:384
msgid ""
"Since WebAssembly does not support virtual memory, the size of the LLVM data "
"stack that is defined both for Wasm Workers but also the main thread will "
"not be possible to grow at runtime. So if the Worker (or the main thread) "
"runs out of stack space, the program behavior will be undefined. Use the "
"Emscripten linker flag -sSTACK_OVERFLOW_CHECK=2 to emit runtime stack "
"overflow checks into the program code to detect these situations during "
"development."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:391
msgid ""
"Note that to avoid the need to perform two separate allocations, the TLS "
"memory for the Wasm Worker will be located at the bottom end (low memory "
"address) of the Wasm Worker stack space."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:396
msgid "Wasm Workers vs the earlier Emscripten Worker API"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:398
msgid ""
"Emscripten provides a second Worker API as part of the emscripten.h header. "
"This Worker API predates the advent of SharedArrayBuffer, and is quite "
"distinct from Wasm Workers API, just the naming of these two APIs is similar "
"due to historical reasons."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:400
msgid ""
"Both APIs allow one to spawn Web Workers from the main thread, though the "
"semantics are different."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:402
msgid ""
"With the Worker API, the user will be able to spawn a Web Worker from a "
"custom URL. This URL can point to a completely separate JS file that was not "
"compiled with Emscripten, to load up Workers from arbitrary URLs. With Wasm "
"Workers, a custom URL is not specified: Wasm Workers will always spawn a Web "
"Worker that computes in the same WebAssembly+JavaScript context as the main "
"program."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:404
msgid ""
"The Worker API does not integrate with SharedArrayBuffer, so interaction "
"with the loaded Worker will always be asynchronous. Wasm Workers however is "
"built on top of SharedArrayBuffer, and each Wasm Worker shares and computes "
"in the same WebAssembly Memory address space of the main thread."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:406
msgid ""
"Both the Worker API and Wasm Workers API provide the user with ability to "
"postMessage() function calls to the Worker. In Worker API, this message "
"posting is restricted to need to originate/initiate from the main thread "
"towards the Worker (using the API ``emscripten_call_worker()`` and "
"``emscripten_worker_respond()`` in ``<emscripten.h>``). With Wasm Workers "
"however one can also postMessage() function calls to their parent (owning) "
"thread."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:408
msgid ""
"If posting function calls with the Emscripten Worker API, it is required "
"that the target Worker URL points to an Emscripten compiled program (so it "
"has the ``Module`` structure to locate function names). Only functions that "
"have been exported to the ``Module`` object are callable. With Wasm Workers, "
"any C/C++ function may be posted, and does not need to be exported."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:410
msgid "Use the Emscripten Worker API when:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:411
msgid ""
"you want to easily spawn a Worker from a JS file that was not built using "
"Emscripten"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:412
msgid ""
"you want to spawn as Worker a single separate compiled program than the main "
"thread program represents, and the main thread and Worker programs do not "
"share common code"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:413
msgid ""
"you do not want to require the use of SharedArrayBuffer, or setting up "
"COOP+COEP headers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:414
msgid ""
"you only need to communicate with the Worker asynchronously using "
"postMessage() function calls"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:416
msgid "Use the Wasm Workers API when:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:417
msgid ""
"you want to create one or more new threads that synchronously compute in the "
"same Wasm Module context"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:418
msgid ""
"you want to spawn multiple Workers from the same codebase and save memory by "
"sharing the WebAssembly Module (object code) and Memory (address space) "
"across the Workers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:419
msgid ""
"you want to synchronously coordinate communication between threads by using "
"atomic primitives and locks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/wasm_workers.rst:420
msgid ""
"your web server has been configured with the needed COOP+COEP headers to "
"enable SharedArrayBuffer capabilities on the site"
msgstr ""

